\begin{tabular}{c|c|c|c}
networks     & S-CNN$_0$ & S-CNN$_1$  & S-CNN$_2$ \\ \hline
mAP$(\%)$         &  17.1     &     19.0    &   18.9        \\ 
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\caption{mAP comparisons between no proposal stage and using the proposal stage of two different networks scales on THUMOS 2014.}
\label{scale}
\end{table}


\noindent\textbf{The classification stage.} Although ${\Theta _{{\rm{loc}}}}$ can replace ${\Theta _{{\rm{cls}}}}$ during prediction, the classification stage is still important because fine-tuning on ${\Theta _{{\rm{cls}}}}$ results in better performance. To study the effects of the classification and localization stages individually, we compare three Segment-CNNs using different settings: (1) \textbf{S-CNN}: keep all three stages and settings in Section \ref{compare}, and ${\Theta _{{\rm{loc}}}}$ is fine-tuned on ${\Theta _{{\rm{cls}}}}$; (2) \textbf{S-CNN (w/o classification)}: remove the classification stage completely and have no ${\Theta _{{\rm{cls}}}}$ to serve as initialization for training ${\Theta _{{\rm{loc}}}}$; (3) \textbf{S-CNN (w/o localization)}: remove the localization stage completely and use classification model ${\Theta _{{\rm{cls}}}}$ to produce predictions. As shown in Figure \ref{top-k}, S-CNN fine-tuned on ${\Theta _{{\rm{cls}}}}$ outperforms S-CNN (w/o classification) consistently when $\kappa$ varies, and consequently the classification stage is necessary during training. Table \ref{map4} lists the average precision for each class when $\kappa=20$K in top-$\kappa$ selection.


